 for bestpractices and # Team Messaging & Notifications

## Overview
Develop a real-time Team Messaging & Notifications subsystem within UnifiedOps that enables: live threaded conversations, user mentions, targeted notification routing (in-app, email, SMS), and digest automation. Provide an integrated experience across Dashboard, Team Messaging Inbox, and Team Messaging Thread pages. Ensure robust runtime safety for all data flows, with explicit guards against null/undefined values before array operations, and proper initialization for React state. Support real-time transport via WebSockets or Server-Sent Events (SSE) with a fallback polling strategy. Include message persistence, search indexing, attachments, mute/pin behavior, unread counts, and token-based authentication/authorization.

---

## Components to Build

1) Real-time Transport Layer (Frontend + Backend)
- Frontend:
  - Establish real-time channel per user or per team room using WebSocket or SSE with automatic reconnect and exponential backoff.
  - Fallback to long-polling when real-time channel is unavailable.
  - Event types: message.new, message.updated, thread.created, thread.archived, user.mentioned, notification.delivered, presence.update.
  - Message composer supports attachments (file uploads with progress), inline previews for images, and mentions (@username) with autocompletion.
- Backend:
  - WebSocket/SSE gateway with per-user channels; scalable approach (use Redis Pub/Sub or a message broker).
  - Message persistence through a messages table; handle delivery guarantees (at-least-once).
  - Presence tracking (online/offline, typing indicator).
  - Rate-limited push for mentions to avoid spam.

2) Message Persistence & Search
- Data models to store messages, threads, channels, attachments, reactions, and read/unread state.
- Full-text search index for messages and threads with support for filtering by user, thread, date, and content.
- Attachments: store metadata (filename, mime-type, size, URL, signed URL exp), and support streaming/downloading.

3) Notifications & Digest Engine
- Notification routing rules:
  - In-app notification per user when they are mentioned, subscribed to a thread, or assigned a task.
  - Email/SMS (Twilio/SendGrid) integration for high-priority or digest delivery per user preferences.
  - Digest automation: daily/weekly digests summarizing unread threads, mentions, and actionable items.
- User preferences: per-channel toggles (in-app, email, SMS), do-not-disturb windows, mute/pin controls, and read receipts.
- Unread counts per thread and global inbox.

4) Inbox (Team Messaging - Inbox)
- UI showing threads list, direct messages, and mentions. Include search, filters (unread, pinned, muted, by user, by channel), and sort (recent activity, unread first).
- Thread overview cards with snippet, last activity timestamp, unread badge, and participant avatars.
- Keyboard shortcuts for compose, search focus, and navigation.

5) Thread View (Team Messaging - Thread)
- Conversation view with:
  - Message history with timestamps, author avatars, and read receipts.
  - Attachments rendering and download/preview.
  - Actions: reply, react, edit (own messages), delete (own messages), pin/unpin, mute thread, mark as unread.
  - Mention parsing with auto-linking to user profiles.
  - Inline reactions and threaded replies (if enabled).
- Attachment uploader with drag-and-drop, progress, and retry logic.
- Real-time updates: new messages append live, message edits reflect instantly, typing indicators.

6) Dashboard (Overview Page)
- KPI panels: unread messages, mentions today, active threads, response SLAs, tasks due.
- Activity feed: a stream of recent messaging events (thread created, message posted, attachments added, mentions).
- Pending tasks integration: show tasks derived from messages or mentions.
- Cashflow snapshot (contextual to notifications, e.g., spending on notifications or action items).
- Quick actions: new thread, new message in a selected thread, mute/unmute thread, set digests.

---

## Implementation Requirements

### Frontend

- Architecture:
  - Componentized React (or framework-equivalent) with TypeScript.
  - State management using React Context + useReducer or a lightweight store (Redux Toolkit or Zustand).
  - Real-time client: a dedicated WebSocket/SSE client module with reconnect/backoff, event normalization, and a safe dispatch mechanism.
  - Data layer: fetchers and hooks (e.g., useQuery-like hooks) with null-safety guards.
- UI Components:
  - InboxLayout: two-column layout with a threads list pane and a thread detail pane (for larger viewports) and a single-column responsive alternative for mobile.
  - ThreadCard: shows thread name, last message excerpt, avatar group, and unread count chip.
  - MessageList: renders messages with avatars, timestamps, attachments, and reactions; supports virtualization for performance.
  - MessageComposer: supports text with mention autocomplete, attachments, and emoji/app capabilities; handles optimistic UI and error fallback.
  - AttachmentPreview: image/video/audio previews; download link; remove option for attachments in draft.
  - Mentions Autocomplete: fetches user directory; keyboard navigable; supports selection with @ key.
  - TypingIndicator: shows who is typing in a thread.
  - NotificationBell / In-App Drawer: shows recent notifications with quick actions.
  - DashboardWidgets: KPI cards, activity feed, quick actions, and digest status indicators.
  - Modals/Toasts: confirm pin/mute, success/error toasts with accessible ARIA roles.
- Data Safety:
  - Ensure all arrays are derived with guards: (array ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(array) ? array.map(...) : [].
  - Initialize state with proper types: useState<Thread[]>([]) for arrays; useState<Message[]>([]) for messages.
  - API shape guards: ensure response?.data is an array before mapping.
  - Optional chaining everywhere for nested API responses.
- Accessibility:
  - Keyboard navigability, aria-labels, proper focus states, high-contrast primary actions, sufficient contrast per WCAG.
- Performance:
  - Lazy-load message histories on thread open; pagination or infinite scroll in long threads.
  - Debounce search input; debounce mention suggestions.
  - Use memoization for expensive renders; avoid unnecessary re-renders.
- Security:
  - JWT/OAuth tokens for API calls; per-room authorization checks; verify user presence and thread membership on activity.
  - Input validation for message content; sanitize strings (prevent XSS).
- Validation:
  - Ensure all user inputs are validated server-side and client-side (length limits, prohibited content).

### Backend

- Data Models (PostgreSQL or your DB of choice; include migrations):
  - users (id, username, email, phone, prefs, etc.)
  - teams (id, name, members)
  - channels (id, team_id, name)
  - threads (id, channel_id, subject, created_by, created_at, updated_at, is_muted, is_pinned, last_message_at)
  - messages (id, thread_id, user_id, content, attachments JSON, created_at, updated_at, is_edited)
  - attachments (id, message_id, url, filename, mime_type, size, uploaded_at)
  - reactions (id, message_id, user_id, type)
  - reads (user_id, thread_id, last_read_at)
  - notifications (id, user_id, thread_id, type, delivered_at, read_at, payload)
  - digests (id, user_id, period, content, delivered_at, status)
  - presence (user_id, online, last_seen, typing_thread_id)
- APIs:
  - POST /api/threads (create thread)
  - GET /api/threads?channel_id=&query=&unread_only=&pin_only=
  - GET /api/threads/{thread_id}/messages?limit=&before=
  - POST /api/messages (send message with optional attachments)
  - PATCH /api/messages/{message_id} (edit)
  - DELETE /api/messages/{message_id}
  - POST /api/messages/{message_id}/attachments (upload)
  - POST /api/threads/{thread_id}/pin / unpin
  - POST /api/threads/{thread_id}/mute / unmute
  - GET /api/notifications (in-app notifications for user)
  - POST /api/notifications/digest (trigger digest generation or scheduled task)
  - GET /api/search/messages?q=
  - POST /api/attachments/sign-url (get signed URLs for uploads)
- Real-time:
  - WebSocket or SSE endpoints per user with channels for threads/chats.
  - Publish/subscribe via Redis or a message broker to deliver events: thread.created, message.added, message.updated, user.mentioned, presence.update.
- Search Indexing:
  - Integrate with a search index (e.g., Elasticsearch or Postgres full-text) for messages and threads; keep in-sync on create/edit/delete.
- Attachments:
  - Storage integration (S3-like) with signed URLs; lifecycle management; access control per user.
- Notifications Engine:
  - Rules engine to route notifications to in-app, email, and SMS based on user preferences and roles.
  - Email templates and Twilio/SendGrid integration with rate limiting and retry policies.
- Validation & Security:
  - Ensure authorization checks for thread access.
  - Input validation with content length limits and profanity filtering if required.
  - Rate limiting for actions like message posting, mentions, and attachments.

### Integration

- Data flow:
  - Client writes a message; server persists message, stores attachments, and emits real-time event to involved users.
  - Mentions trigger in-app notifications and optional outbound emails/SMS per user settings.
  - Unread counts are computed per user by reads table and updated on activity.
  - Digest engine aggregates notifications into periodic summaries for users who opt-in.
- Cross-page synchronization:
  - Inbox and Thread views listen to real-time events and refresh appropriately.
  - Dashboard KPIs subscribe to message/notification streams to reflect live activity.
- Error handling:
  - Fallback UI when real-time transport fails; provide retry controls and clear user messaging.
  - Graceful degradation for offline mode with local caching and later synchronization.

---

## User Experience Flow

1) User logs in and lands on Dashboard.
   - Sees KPI widgets: unread messages, mentions, active threads, pending actions, and digest status.
   - Quick action: New Thread button accessible from Dashboard.
2) User opens Team Messaging - Inbox.
   - Left pane shows Threads and Direct Messages with avatars and latest activity.
   - Search bar filters by thread subject, last message snippet, or participant names.
   - Clicks a thread to open; right pane shows the conversation.
   - Mentions are highlighted; user can click a name to view profile or start a direct message.
3) In a Thread, user composes a message.
   - Mention autocomplete activates on typing @; selecting a user inserts a mention.
   - Attachments can be added; progress bars display, and on success attachments render in the message.
   - Send message; message appears instantly (optimistic UI) and persists to backend.
   - Other participants see typing indicator and new message in real-time.
   - User can react to messages, pin/unpin the thread, or mute it.
4) Notification Routing.
   - If user is mentioned, they receive an in-app notification and a digest check is queued per their preferences.
   - High-priority mentions can trigger email or SMS per user settings.
   - Digest jobs run (daily/weekly) to summarize unread items and mentions.
5) Real-time synchronization.
   - All connected users see live updates as messages arrive, threads are created or updated, or presence changes.
6) Accessibility and responsiveness.
   - UI works on desktop and mobile; accessible via keyboard and screen readers; color scheme adheres to the given design tokens.

---

## Technical Specifications

- Data Models: See above (Users, Teams, Channels, Threads, Messages, Attachments, Reactions, Reads, Notifications, Digests, Presence)
- API Endpoints: See Backend section for routes and methods
- Security:
  - Authentication: JWT/OAuth with access tokens; refresh tokens where applicable.
  - Authorization: Verify user membership in team/channel/thread; enforce thread-level tenant scoping.
  - Data protection: Encrypted in transit (TLS), proper access-controlled signed URLs for attachments.
- Validation:
  - Message content: max length, disallowed content checks; sanitize before storage.
  - Attachment: size limits, file type checks on client and server.
  - Search: guard against injection; ensure sanitized query parameters.
- Data Safety Rules (MANDATORY):
  - Supabase-like patterns translated to your stack:
    - Always use data ?? [] when handling query results.
    - Guard array methods with (array ?? []).map(...) or Array.isArray(array) ? array.map(...) : [].
    - Initialize React state for arrays/objects: useState<Type[]>([]) and useState<Message[]>([]) etc.
    - Validate API responses: const list = Array.isArray(response?.data) ? response.data : [].
    - Use optional chaining for nested API responses: obj?.prop?.nested.
    - Destructure with defaults: const { items = [], count = 0 } = response ?? {}.

